        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2336414409?book_show_action=true">Mar 22, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Addy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Addy" href="/user/show/9299164-addy">Addy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/9299164-addy?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2336414409" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1029351391867507649">The idea of two kidnappers snatching a 10-year-old (who turns the tables on them) is the kind of hilarity HOME ALONE took full advantage of. But this farce, short as it is at 15 pages, runs out of gas very very soon. The boy is just pure evil and it boggles the mind that, unlike Joe Pesci, none of these bumbling criminals attempt to cause their &quot;victim&quot; actual harm. O. Henry&apos;s famous for his twist endings—in this case neither the story nor the ending make much sense. Yet it is hard not to enjoy </span>
  <span id="freeText1029351391867507649" style="display:none">The idea of two kidnappers snatching a 10-year-old (who turns the tables on them) is the kind of hilarity HOME ALONE took full advantage of. But this farce, short as it is at 15 pages, runs out of gas very very soon. The boy is just pure evil and it boggles the mind that, unlike Joe Pesci, none of these bumbling criminals attempt to cause their "victim" actual harm. O. Henry's famous for his twist endings—in this case neither the story nor the ending make much sense. Yet it is hard not to enjoy or be impressed by the dazzling writing style.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1029351391867507649" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


